sentence: San Francisco.
Oakland.
Palo Alto.
Berkeley.
San Jose.
In the span of several dozen miles on the coast of California, several of the country's most beautiful cities stand proud.
Beyond its beauty, this area is remarkable for its innovative businesses.
Home to the world famous Silicon Valley, the San Francisco Bay Area is one of the most important hubs for technology in the world.
Of course, this also means the region always commands the attention of Wall Street.
The Bay Area is home to some absolutely massive companies, but that doesn't mean every one of them is a good investment.

Here are a few good picks for investors looking to buy a San Francisco-based stock right now:

Alphabet Inc. GOOGL , the new conglomerate launched as the parent company of Google, calls a mid-sized town on the banks of the Bay home.
The restructuring, along with the leadership of new CFO Ruth Porat, promises to rein in spending and increase efficiency.

Whether Alphabet can effectively accomplish this in the long-term remains to be seen, but Google was one of the most successful tech stocks in 2015, and a Zacks Rank #2 (Buy) and expected earnings growth of over 20% could make this stock a good pick.
Still confused about the new Alphabet Inc. restructuring?
Check out our A to Z Guide to Alphabet .
Located just a few hundred feet from the banks of the eastern waterfront, Salesforce's CRM headquarters is right in the heart of San Francisco.
Employees must love the location as much as Salesforce's investors liked the company's 2015 stock performance.
Shares of CRM gained over 30% last year.
While the first few days of 2016 saw shares of Salesforce slump, most available metrics indicate that the company should have a good year.
In the past 60 days, we have seen 9 positive estimate revisions for the company's earnings through January, 2017, and demand for quality cloud computing should continue to increase.
Foster City lies about half way between San Francisco and San Jose and is home to Gilead Sciences GILD , one of the biggest names in the biopharmaceutical industry.

While 2015 was an up and down year for Gilead investors, the company is in a solid position right now thanks to the approval of its HIV treatment Genvoya, first tenofoviralafenamide (TAF)-based regimen to receive FDA approval.
The strength of this stock is best exemplified by its Style Score grades: "A" in value, "B" in growth, and "B" in momentum.
Value-minded investors are loving the Gilead's Forward PE of 8.21 and PEG Ratio of 0.86.
The San Francisco Bay Area is beautiful, and the company's that call it home are constantly driving the technology, health, and business worlds.
Wall Street may be on the opposite end of the country, but investors never take their eyes off of 'Frisco.
These three companies in particular are the crown jewels of the "Golden City."
